Assist Tumor Detection & Localization by Transfer Learning Classification Model Developed on Small Datasets¶

Kun Tao¶

Goal¶

Given a set of gigapixel pathology images, this project aims to develop a classification model which outputs a heatmap showing regions of a biopsy image likely to contain cancer. It is worth to mention that the goal is to build a thoughtful, end-to-end prototype - not to match the accuracy from the paper, or use all the available CAMELYON16 data.

Data Shared by Prof. Gordon¶

The original slides and annotations in the CAMELYON16 data are in an unusual format. Prof. Josh Gordon converted a bunch of them and shared his data folder with us, which contains all the slides and tumor masks that he converted and are supposed to be plenty for this project, so we can read them with OpenSlide.

My Own Reorganized Data¶

First, I added Josh's shared folder to my own Google Drive, then I copied and moved all files to a newly created folder kt_slides in the drive. Slide 038 does not have the corresponding mask and slide 099 only has the .xml file, so they were discarded. Totally, I have 21 slides left and I randomly split the rest files into two sets and respectively moved them into the newly created subfolders of train_val_slides and test_slides. Thus, there are 18 slides and corresponding masks and xmls in the train_val_slides subfolder, and 3 slides and corresponding masks and xmls in the test_slides subfolder. It is worth to mention that the tissue-pixel percentage in slide 001, 002, 005, 012, 016, 019, 023, 031, 035, 057, 059 and 064 was pretty low, less than 4% at Level 3 (the tissue-pixel percentage will further decrease when the zooming level goes up to Level 0, but slightly increase when the zooming level goes down.), and patches extracted from these slides were mostly background patches which were discarded before training the model to save the computational cost.

Methods Overview¶

Data Preparation¶

After installing the OpenSlide, importing necessary libraries/modules and mouting the drive, I created the patches directory and its subfolders in the Colab to store small images extracted from slides and masks later on. For instance, a tumor-positive patch of size 299 x 299 extracted from a slide in the train_val_slides will be saved to /content/patches/slide_patch/train/1.0 with a probability of 0.8, or to /content/patches/slide_patch/validation/1.0 with a probability of 0.2, which is roughly equivalent to split patches from the train_val_slides with a ratio of 80 to 20 into the training set and the validation set. The relevant tumor-positive mask patch will be correspondingly saved to either /content/patches/mask_patch/train/1.0 or /content/patches/mask_patch/validation/1.0. Similar processing was applied to extract tumor-negative patches.

Next, I extracted patches with a size of 299 x 299 from every pair of slide and mask by looping through train_val_slides folder in the mounted Google Drive, and respectively save them into the aforementioned subfolders under the patches directory in the Colab.

Before going to the next step, I decided to perform Sanity Checks from two perspectives: a) visualize the zooming effect with respect to a randomly picked slide of tumor_091.tif; b) visualize two randomly picked tumor-positive patches with one from the training set and the other from the validation set.

Built Model by Transfer Learning¶

I built my classifiction model by taking the convolutional base from the InceptionV3, freezing the base, then adding one GlobalAveragePooling2D layer and two Dense layers on top of it. The first Dense layer has 32 units and activation = 'relu', whereas the second Dense layer is the output layer with a single unit and activation = 'sigmoid'. The optimizer chosen for my model was Adam with a learning rate of 1e-5, the loss was set as binary_crossentropy.

Handle Imbalanced Data¶

a) Use class_weight during Training¶

To combat the highly imbalanced classes, I sepcified the class_weight to 'tell' the model to 'pay more attention' to the underrepresented, class 1 patches which are tumor-positive.

b) Use a Set of Weighted Metrics during Training and Testing¶

In addition, I selected a set of metrics to fully evaluate the classifiction performance instead of just using accuracy, and I also make the model to weight these metrics during training and testing besides just weighting the loss function during training. Here are the metrics I used: True Positive, False Positive, True Negative, False Negative, Binary Accuracy, Precision, Recall and AUC. Consequently, curves of training and validation accuracy/loss, precision, recall and AUC versus epoch were plotted, which look quite reasonable.

Evaluate Model Performance on Test Set¶

After the model was trained, I generated a set of non-overlapping patches for each pair of slide and mask in the test_slides folder in my mounted Google Drive. Then, I performed a Sanity Check by visualizing two randomly picked test patches with one being tumor-positive and the other being tumor-negative for each testing slide.

Finally, I used the trained model to make Slide-level Tumor Prediction for each test slide, created Confusion Matrix, ROC Curve, and output Heatmap for each test slide. It is worth to mention that for a better visual check, I highlighted the predicted probability heatmap by setting all probabilities < 0.5 as zero, and overlaid the relevant tumor mask on top of it. Thus, it is easier to see how well the model classification matched the ground truth, and where the model predictions missed the tumors.

# See https://openslide.org/api/python/#openslide.OpenSlide.read_region
# Note: x,y coords are with respect to level 0.
# There is an example below of working with coordinates
# with respect to a higher zoom level.

# Read a region from the slide
# Return a numpy RBG array
def read_slide(slide, x, y, level, width, height, as_float=False):
    im = slide.read_region((x,y), level, (width, height))
    im = im.convert('RGB') # drop the alpha channel
    if as_float:
        im = np.asarray(im, dtype=np.float32)
    else:
        im = np.asarray(im)
    assert im.shape == (height, width, 3)
    return im

Extract Patches from Every Pair of Slide and Tumor Mask in the train_val_slides¶

In the following code block, small patches of size 299 x 299 were extracted from each slide and relevant tumor mask. The stride of the sliding window was 128. If there was at least one tissue-pixel in a slide patch, then I further checked if there was at least one tumor-pixel in the center region with a size of 128 x 128 pixels in the corresponding tumor mask patch. If so, I would either respectively save the slide and mask patches to the corresponding train/1.0 subfolders with a probability 0.8, or save to the relevant validation/1.0 subfolders with a probability 0.2. Similar processing was applied to non-tumor patches who do contain at least one tissue-pixel.

In [0]:
stride_train_val = 128
half_stride_train_val = int(stride_train_val / 2)
print("stride_train_val: {}".format(stride_train_val))

width_patch = 299
height_patch = 299
width_patch_half = ceil(299 / 2)
height_patch_half = ceil(299 / 2)

idx_patch = 0
L_patches_labels = []
for slide_path, tumor_mask_path in zip(train_slide_paths, train_tumor_mask_paths):

  #========================================================================================
  slide = open_slide(str(slide_path))
  print ("Read WSI from %s with width: %d, height: %d" % (slide_path, 
                                                          slide.level_dimensions[0][0], 
                                                          slide.level_dimensions[0][1]))

  tumor_mask = open_slide(str(tumor_mask_path))
  print ("Read tumor mask from %s" % (tumor_mask_path))

  print("Slide includes %d levels" % len(slide.level_dimensions))

  levels = []
  res = []
  down_factors = []

  for i in range(len(slide.level_dimensions)):
      print("Level %d, dimensions: %s downsample factor %d" % (i, 
                                                              slide.level_dimensions[i], 
                                                              slide.level_downsamples[i]))
      ####assert tumor_mask.level_dimensions[i][0] == slide.level_dimensions[i][0]
      ####assert tumor_mask.level_dimensions[i][1] == slide.level_dimensions[i][1]
      levels.append(i)
      res.append(slide.level_dimensions[i])
      down_factors.append(slide.level_downsamples[i])

  # Verify downsampling works as expected
  width, height = slide.level_dimensions[7]
  assert width * slide.level_downsamples[7] == slide.level_dimensions[0][0]
  assert height * slide.level_downsamples[7] == slide.level_dimensions[0][1]

  current_train_slide_name = str(slide_path).rsplit('/', 1)[-1]

  #========================================================================================
  #========================================================================================
  # Use the sliding window approach discussed in class to collect training
  # data for your classifier. E.g., slide a window across the slide (for
  # starters, use a zoomed out view, so you're not working with giant images).
  # Save each window to disk as an image. To find the label for that image, 
  # check to the tissue mask to see if the same region contains cancerous cells.

  # Important: this is tricky to get right. Carefully debug your pipeline before
  # training your model. Start with just a single image, and a relatively 
  # low zoom level.

  intensity = 0.8

  L = levels[down_factors.index(int(down_factors[-1] / 32))]
  print("Selected level to train the model with respect to slide {}: {}".format(current_train_slide_name, L))

  width_L = res[L][0]
  height_L = res[L][1]
  down_L = int(down_factors[L])
  print("Level {} resolution: {}".format(L, (width_L, height_L)))
  print("Level {} downsample factor: {}".format(L, down_L))
  print("Level {} means {}X magnification here\n\n".format(L, int(down_factors[-1] / down_factors[L])))

  x_patches_train_val = ceil(width_L / stride_train_val)
  y_patches_train_val = ceil(height_L / stride_train_val)

  for yy in range(y_patches_train_val):
    for xx in range(x_patches_train_val):
      x_L0 = stride_train_val * xx * down_L
      y_L0 = stride_train_val * yy * down_L
      slide_image_patch = read_slide(slide, 
                                     x = x_L0, 
                                     y = y_L0, 
                                     level = L, 
                                     width = width_patch,
                                     height = height_patch) 
      
      patch_gray = rgb2gray(slide_image_patch)
      assert patch_gray.shape == (slide_image_patch.shape[0], slide_image_patch.shape[1])
      no_tissue_pixel = np.all(patch_gray > intensity)

      if no_tissue_pixel:
        continue
      else:
        mask_image_patch = read_slide(tumor_mask, 
                                      x = x_L0, 
                                      y = y_L0, 
                                      level = L, 
                                      width = width_patch, 
                                      height = height_patch)[:, :, 0]
        
        mask_ctr_region = mask_image_patch[height_patch_half - half_stride_train_val : height_patch_half + half_stride_train_val, 
                                           width_patch_half - half_stride_train_val : width_patch_half + half_stride_train_val] 

        slide_im = Image.fromarray(slide_image_patch)
        mask_im = Image.fromarray(mask_image_patch)

        if np.any(mask_ctr_region == 1):
          L_patches_labels.append(1.0)

          train_or_val_1 = np.random.choice(2, 1, p = [0.8, 0.2])
          train_or_val_1 = train_or_val_1.item()
          if train_or_val_1 == 0:
            slide_im.save('/content/patches/slide_patch/train/1.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '.tif')
            mask_im.save('/content/patches/mask_patch/train/1.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '_mask.tif')
          else:
            slide_im.save('/content/patches/slide_patch/validation/1.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '.tif')
            mask_im.save('/content/patches/mask_patch/validation/1.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '_mask.tif')
        else:
          L_patches_labels.append(0.0)
          
          train_or_val_0 = np.random.choice(2, 1, p = [0.8, 0.2])
          train_or_val_0 = train_or_val_0.item()
          if train_or_val_0 == 0:
            slide_im.save('/content/patches/slide_patch/train/0.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '.tif')
            mask_im.save('/content/patches/mask_patch/train/0.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '_mask.tif')
          else:
            slide_im.save('/content/patches/slide_patch/validation/0.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '.tif')
            mask_im.save('/content/patches/mask_patch/validation/0.0/' + str(idx_patch) + '_mask.tif')

        idx_patch = idx_patch + 1

label_ones = L_patches_labels.count(1.0)   
label_zeros = L_patches_labels.count(0.0) 
print("There are {} patches in class 1 (tumor)".format(label_ones))
print("There are {} patches in class 0 (non-tumor)".format(label_zeros))
print("Total patches from {} training slides: {}\n".format(train_slide_paths_count, len(L_patches_labels)))

Sanity Check on Zoom Levels¶

In the following code block, the center region with 128 x 128 pixels was taken from the sldie tumor_091.tif at Level 7 and shown in the first Level-7 subplot. Then, the upper left quadrant at the Level-7 subplot was zoomed in and shown in the second Level-6 subplot. Repeat this process until the zoom level reaches 128X at Level 0. As we see, the top left pixel in the Level-7 subplot was eventually magnified 128X as shown in the last subplot.

In [0]:
# Example: read the entire slide at level 5

# Higher zoom levels may not fit into memory.
# You can use the below function to extract regions from higher zoom levels 
# without having to read the entire image into ram.

# Use the sliding window approach discussed in class to collect training
# data for your classifier. E.g., slide a window across the slide (for
# starters, use a zoomed out view, so you're not working with giant images).
# Save each window to disk as an image. To find the label for that image, 
# check to the tissue mask to see if the same region contains cancerous cells.

# Important: this is tricky to get right. Carefully debug your pipeline before
# training your model. Start with just a single image, and a relatively 
# low zoom level.

slide_path_example = '/content/drive/My Drive/kt_slides/train_val_slides/tumor_091.tif'
slide_example = open_slide(slide_path_example)
slide_example_image_L7 = read_slide(slide_example , 
                                    x = 0, 
                                    y = 0, 
                                    level = 7, 
                                    width = slide_example.level_dimensions[7][0], 
                                    height = slide_example.level_dimensions[7][1])

slide_example_name = slide_path_example.rsplit('/', 1)[-1]
res_example = slide_example.level_dimensions[7] 

x0_7 = int(res_example[0] / 2 - 64)
y0_7 = int(res_example[1] / 2 - 64)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize = (4, 4), dpi = 100)
ax.imshow(slide_example_image_L7)
rect1 = patches.Rectangle((x0_7, y0_7), 128, 128, linewidth = 3, edgecolor = 'springgreen', facecolor = 'none')
ax.add_patch(rect1)
ax.set_title(slide_example_name + ' at Level 7 with a 128 x 128 central bounding box ', fontsize = 10)

#===============================================================================
patch_128x128_list = []
rev_levels = [7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0]
for i in rev_levels:
  patch_128x128 = read_slide(slide_example, 
                             x = x0_7 * 128, 
                             y = y0_7 * 128, 
                             level = i, 
                             width = 128, 
                             height = 128)
  
  patch_128x128_list.append(patch_128x128)
 

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 4, figsize = (12, 6), dpi = 100)
fig.subplots_adjust(wspace = 0.3, hspace = 0.15, top = 0.92)
fig.suptitle('The top left pixel at Level 7 is magnified up to 128X', fontsize = 10)

mag = 1
for i in range(2):
  for j in range(4):
    ax[i][j].imshow(patch_128x128_list[i * 4 + j])
    rect2 = patches.Rectangle((0, 0), 1 * mag, 1 * mag, linewidth = 3, edgecolor = 'r',facecolor = 'none')
    ax[i][j].add_patch(rect2)
    if (i * 4 + j) == 0: 
      ax[i][j].set_title('Level ' + str(7 - (i * 4 + j)), fontsize = 10)
    else:
      ax[i][j].set_title('Level ' + str(7 - (i * 4 + j)) + ': ' + str(mag) + 'X Zoom In', fontsize = 10)
      
    mag = mag * 2

Build My Model by Using the Convolution Base of the InceptionV3¶

The following two code blocks shows how to build my own classification model by using Transfer Learning.

First, I took the convolutional base from the InceptionV3 by excluding the top but keeping the pretrained weights. Then I froze the convolutional base, added a GlobalAveragePooling2D layer and two Dense layers on top of it. The last Dense layer with a single unit and activation = 'sigmoid' is the output layer.

The summary of the model was shown at the end of the second code block.

In [0]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications import InceptionV3

IMG_SHAPE = (299, 299, 3)
conv_base = InceptionV3(include_top = False,
                        weights = 'imagenet',
                        input_shape = IMG_SHAPE)
conv_base.trainable = False

from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Dropout, GlobalAveragePooling2D, Dense, Flatten, Input
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model, Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint

x = conv_base.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = Dense(32, activation = 'relu')(x)
prediction = Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid')(x)

model = Model(inputs = conv_base.input, outputs = prediction)

model.summary()

Use a Set of Metrics to fully Evaluate the Classification Performance on Highly Imbalanced Dataset¶

As we can see from what was printed below, the extracted patches are highly imbalanced. Obviously for data like this, it is not enough to judge the classification performance with accuracy alone. Therefore, I employed the following set of metrics instead:

1) True Positives (tp): in this case, it means that tumor-positive patches are correctly identified as tumor-positive (labeled as 1.0)

2) False Positives (fp): in this case, it means that tumor-negative patches are incorrectly identified as tumor-positive (labeled as 1.0)

3) True Negatives (tn): in this case, it means that tumor-negative patches are correctly identified as tumor-negative (labeled as 0.0)

4) False Negatives (fn): in this case, it means that tumor-positive patches are incorrectly identified as tumor-negative (labeled as 0.0)

5) Accuracy: the fraction of predictions my model got right. In this case, it is equal to (tp + tn) / (tp + fp + tn + fn)

6) Precision: in this case, it means that proportion of predicted tumor-positive was actually correct. It is calculated by tp / (tp + fp)

7) Recall: in this case, it means that proportion of actual tumor-positive was identified correctly, and it is calculated by tp / (tp + fn)

8) AUC: in this case, it refers to the Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve. This metric is equal to the probability that a classifier will rank a random positive sample higher than a random negative sample. For a reasonable well classifier, the AUC should be above 0.5, which means the classifier performs better than random guessing. If AUC = 0.5, the classifier is basically worthless, as its predictive ability is no better than random guessing. If AUC < 0.5, the model actually performs worse than random guessing, which likely indicates something is wrong in the data.

If the classification model demonstrates both high Precision and high Recall, then it is highly dependable, namely, it doesn't misclassify healthy patients and it doesn’t incorrectly leave out breast cancer patients.

If the model shows low Recall but high Precision, then the model will miss lots of real patients, which might be a pretty bad scenario in terms of cancer detection.

If the model shows a high Recall but low Precision, it means that the model is able to detect tumors well but ends up creating a lot of false alarms. However, in terms of cancer detection, it perhaps would be better to classify a few healthy patients as cancer patients than vice versa.

Briefly speaking, the best model would be a high Precision and high Recall model. If that is too hard to achieve, in terms of cancer detection, we prefer a high Recall model with a reasonable Precision, that is, a high sensitivity model with some false alarms.

It is worth to point out that I set the weighted_metrics in the following model.compile method, which means besides the weighted loss function during training, all above metrics will be evaluated and weighted by the class_weight specified later on during training and testing.

In [0]:
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

my_metrics = [tf.keras.metrics.TruePositives(name = 'tp'),
              tf.keras.metrics.FalsePositives(name = 'fp'),
              tf.keras.metrics.TrueNegatives(name = 'tn'),
              tf.keras.metrics.FalseNegatives(name = 'fn'), 
              tf.keras.metrics.BinaryAccuracy(name = 'accuracy'),
              tf.keras.metrics.Precision(name = 'precision'),
              tf.keras.metrics.Recall(name = 'recall'),
              tf.keras.metrics.AUC(name = 'auc'),
]

model.compile(optimizer = Adam(lr = 1e-5),
              loss = 'binary_crossentropy',
              metrics = my_metrics,
              weighted_metrics = my_metrics)

Use class_weight to Handle Highly Imbalanced Classes, Enable Early Stopping, and Finally Save the Trained Model¶

In [0]:
label_ones = L_patches_labels.count(1.0)   
label_zeros = L_patches_labels.count(0.0) 
print("label_ones: {}".format(label_ones))
print("label_zeros: {}".format(label_zeros))

weight_for_0 = len(L_patches_labels) / (label_zeros * 2.0) 
weight_for_1 = len(L_patches_labels) / (label_ones * 2.0)
class_weights = {0: weight_for_0, 1: weight_for_1}
print("class_weights: {}\n".format(class_weights))

print("There are {} patches in class 1 in the training set".format(y_train_cnts[1]))
print("There are {} patches in class 1 in the validation set\n".format(y_val_cnts[1]))


early_stopping = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_loss', 
                                                  verbose = 1,
                                                  patience = 10,
                                                  mode = 'auto',
                                                  restore_best_weights = True)


n_epochs = 30
model_history = model.fit(train_generator,
                          steps_per_epoch = train_generator.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                          epochs = n_epochs,
                          callbacks = [early_stopping],
                          validation_data = validation_generator,
                          validation_steps = validation_generator.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                          class_weight = class_weights)

model.save("/content/kt_project_model.h5")

Plot Curves of Training and Validation Accuracy/Loss versus Epoch¶

def plot_acc_loss(history):
  acc = history.history['accuracy_1']
  val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy_1']
  loss = history.history['loss']
  val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

  epochs = tf.range(1, len(acc) + 1, 1)

  fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (12, 6))
  plt.subplots_adjust(wspace = 0.3, hspace = 0.3)
  ax[0].set_title('Training and validation accuracy')
  ax[0].plot(epochs, acc, color='blue', label='Train')
  ax[0].plot(epochs, val_acc, color='orange', label='Val')
  ax[0].set_xticks(np.arange(0, len(acc) + 2, 2))
  ax[0].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[0].set_ylabel('Accuracy')
  ax[0].legend()
  ax[0].yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(1))

  ax[1].set_title('Training and validation loss')
  ax[1].plot(epochs, loss, color='blue', label='Train')
  ax[1].plot(epochs, val_loss, color='orange', label='Val')
  ax[1].set_xticks(np.arange(0, len(acc) + 2, 2))
  ax[1].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[1].set_ylabel('Loss')
  ax[1].legend()

plot_acc_loss(model_history)

Plot Curves of Training and Validation AUC, Precision and Recall versus Epoch¶

The Training AUC is around 0.95, whereas the Validation AUC is about 0.85, which means predictions made by the model were much better than random guessing.

Both training and validation Precision look reasonably well. Overall the validation Precision was even higher than the training Precision after the 8th epoch, Futher investigation is desirable to interpret the reason.

The model demonstrated a pretty high Recall on the training set, but the validation Recall was fluctuating around 0.4, which needs to be further improved.

def plot_auc_precision_recall(history):
  auc = history.history['auc_1']
  val_auc = history.history['val_auc_1']

  precision = history.history['precision_1']
  val_precision = history.history['val_precision_1']
  
  recall = history.history['recall_1']
  val_recall = history.history['val_recall_1']

  epochs = tf.range(1, len(auc) + 1, 1)

  fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize = (18, 6))
  plt.subplots_adjust(wspace = 0.35, hspace = 0.3)
  ax[0].set_title('Training and validation AUC')
  ax[0].plot(epochs, auc, color='blue', label='Train')
  ax[0].plot(epochs, val_auc, color='orange', label='Val')
  ax[0].set_xticks(np.arange(0, len(auc) + 2, 2))
  ax[0].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[0].set_ylabel('AUC')
  ax[0].legend()

  ax[1].set_title('Training and validation Precision')
  ax[1].plot(epochs, precision, color='blue', label='Train')
  ax[1].plot(epochs, val_precision, color='orange', label='Val')
  ax[1].set_xticks(np.arange(0, len(auc) + 2, 2))
  ax[1].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[1].set_ylabel('Precision')
  ax[1].legend()

  ax[2].set_title('Training and validation Recall')
  ax[2].plot(epochs, recall, color='blue', label='Train')
  ax[2].plot(epochs, val_recall, color='orange', label='Val')
  ax[2].set_xticks(np.arange(0, len(auc) + 2, 2))
  ax[2].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[2].set_ylabel('Recall')
  ax[2].legend()

Generate Confusion Matrix and ROC Curve for Each Test Slide¶

A confusion matrix is a table that is often used to describe the performance of a classification model on a set of testing data for which the true values are known. It gives a visualization of the model performance.

In a confusion matrix, the number of correct and incorrect predictions are summarized with count values and broken down by each class. Therefore, a confusion matrix not only gives us insight into the errors being made by a classifier but also the types of errors that are being made.

Confusion Matrices obtained from three testing slides are promising, especially for the second slide tumor_094.tif, the model only missed 2 tumor-positive patches.

As for the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve, it is a graph showing the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds. More specifically, it plots True Positive Rate (TPR) versus False Positive Rate (FPR) at different classification thresholds. TPR is also know as recall and defined as tp / (tp + fn). FPR is defined as fp / (fp + tn). The top left corner of the plot is the ideal point: a false positive rate of zero, and a true positive rate of one, which is not very realistic, but it does mean that a larger area under the curve (AUC) is usually better.

Look at these three ROC curves, I'd like to say the model did a much better job than random guessing.

def plot_cm_roc(img_name, data_name, labels, preds_prob, p):

  preds = (preds_prob > p).astype(int)

  fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (8, 3), dpi = 100)
  fig.subplots_adjust(wspace = 0.35, hspace = 0.0, top = 0.80)
  fig.suptitle('Confusion Matrix, ROC Curve and Heatmap for ' + img_name, fontsize = 12)

  # plot confusion matrix
  cm = confusion_matrix(labels, preds)
  sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = "d", ax = ax[0])
  ax[0].set_title('Confusion matrix @p = {:.2f}'.format(p), fontsize = 10)
  ax[0].set_ylabel('Actual label', fontsize = 10)
  ax[0].set_xlabel('Predicted label', fontsize = 10)

  
  # plot roc curve
  fp, tp, _ = roc_curve(labels, preds_prob)
  roc_auc = roc_auc_score(labels, preds_prob)

  ax[1].plot(fp, tp, label = data_name + ' (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc, color = 'orange')
  ax[1].plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color = 'navy', linestyle = '--')
  ax[1].set_xlabel('False positive rate', fontsize = 10)
  ax[1].set_ylabel('True positive rate', fontsize = 10)
  ax[1].set_title('ROC Curve', fontsize = 10)
  ax[1].grid(True)
  ax[1].set_aspect('equal')
  ax[1].legend(loc = 'lower right', fontsize = 8)

  plt.show()

Generate Heatmap for Each Test Slide¶

The model produced a comparable heatmap for each testing slide.

The sigmoid activation in the last layer of the model outputs a probability, indicating how likely a patch is in class 1. By setting all probabilities less than 0.5 as zero, I eventually got a heatmap which highlights those patches that have a probability greater than 0.5, namely, patches are predicted as tumor-positive.

After overlapping the aforementioned heatmap with the given tumor mask for each testing slide and put the overlaid heatmap and the tumor mask side by side, it is easy to see the model correctly classified some positive patches which match the given mask although it also missed some spots.

Overall, heatmaps output from the model are comparable. Further improvements need to be done to lower the false negatives and false positives.

Conclusions and Future Work¶

Overall, transfer learning from the InceptionV3 architecture pretrained on the ImageNet did a good job in terms of the following aspects regarding three randomly picked testing slides tumor_078.tif, tumor_094.tif and tumor_110.tif:

1) the slide-level tumor-positive probabilities predicted by the model are respectively about 0.87, 0.91 and 0.96.

2) all three confusion matrices look decent: pretty high true negatives, reasonably good true positives, false positives and false negatives.

3) nice-looking ROC curves which demonstrate that predictions made by the model are much better than random guessing in general.

However, the model does need to be further improved, especially on how to produce a better heatmap. Possible ways to achieve that might be:

1) have an in-depth analysis on why false negatives and false positives were relatively high, and figure out how to lower them.

2) apply fine-tuning to the model built by transfer learning to further boost the classification performance, such as increasing the true positives, lowering the false negatives and positives, etc., to produce a heatmap matching the ground truth better.

3) most images in the ImageNet might be quite different from the biopsy images for breast cancer detection. Consequently, weights pretrained on the ImageNet perhaps is not a very good choice for classification tasks in medical imaging. It is worth to consider training a model from the scratch.

4) use more advanced image processing algorithms to produce the binary mask from the original probability heatmap instead of just using the threshold of p > 0.5.
